  <script id="ads-targetting">
   function getTempRange(item) {
              let tempRange = 'ERROR';
              if (item) {
                const tempFloor = Math.floor(item / 5) * 5;
                tempRange = tempFloor + ' to ' + (tempFloor + 4);
              }
              return tempRange;
            }

            let objId, objType;
            if ('' === 'story' || '' === 'video' || '' === 'gallery') {
              objId = 'whio/';
              objType = '';
            } else {
              const pathname = window.location.pathname;
              objType = 'index';
              if (pathname.length >= 35) {
                objId = 'whio' + pathname.slice(pathname.length - 35, pathname.length);
              } else {
                objId = 'whio' + pathname;
              }
            }

            window.googletag = window.googletag || {};
            window.googletag.cmd = window.googletag.cmd || [];
            window.googletag.cmd.push(function() {
              window.googletag.pubads().setTargeting('weather', 33 + '')
                .setTargeting('temp_range', getTempRange(34))
                .setTargeting('sky', 'Fair')
                .setTargeting('obj_id', objId)
                .setTargeting('type_name', objType)
              })
  </script>

  <script>
   // variation of uuid algorithm with date time added
          function ppid() {
            var a = 'xyx' + Math.round(Date.now() / 1000) + 'xxxxxxxxxxxxxxyxxxxxxxxxxxx';
            return a.replace(/[xy]/g, function(c) {
              var r = Math.random() * 16 | 0, v = c == 'x' ? r : (r & 0x3 | 0x8);
              return v.toString(16);
            });
          }

        var cmgCookieString = 'uniqueCMGVisitor';
        var uniqueCMGVisitor = ppid();
        if (Cookies.get(cmgCookieString)) {
            // if the cookie exists reset it with the same value and set it to expire in 30 days
            var uniqueValue = Cookies.get(cmgCookieString);
            Cookies.set(cmgCookieString, uniqueValue, { 'expires': 30 })
        } else {
            // if it doesn't exist set it with a new value to expire in 30 days
            Cookies.set(cmgCookieString, uniqueCMGVisitor, { 'expires': 30 });
        }
  </script>

am one of the newest members of the WHIO team, joining Cox Media Group in May 2013. I have started out my career as an anchor, reporter, and producer for WHIO-AM/FM and will also report on traffic for both radio and WHIO-TV. In my short time with the company I am grateful for learning and working with some of the best in the industry.\n\nI was born in Hamilton, Ohio and attended one of the GCL’s finest schools, Stephen T. Badin High School. It was during my time at Badin I discovered what I wanted to do for my career as I fell in love with the broadcasting industry. I was the public address announcer for many sporting events at Badin, and I had a desire to take the next step into radio and television as a play by play man. If I couldn’t play sports, I wanted to be around them. \n\nI came to Dayton to pursue my dream of working in the media by attending the University of Dayton. I graduated Cum Laude with a degree in Communication with a concentration in Electronic Media and a minor in History. My time at UD directly affected my personal and professional development. I was very active in many parts of campus, mostly the student radio station WUDR and the honors communication fraternity Phi Beta Chi. At WUDR I was a manager for three years, first as the Public Affairs and Sports Director for one year, and a combined role of General Manager and Sports Director for two. I also held the position of Vice President for one term with PBX.\n\nLike previous sports directors before me, doing play by play for WUDR led to some great opportunities, including traveling to the Atlantic 10 Tournament in Atlantic City, New Jersey twice and Brooklyn, New York once. My first year in Atlantic City saw the Flyers make an improbable run to the championship game, but fell short in the final game. Two of my childhood idols, Verne Lundquist and Bill Raftery, calling the game for CBS, featured my crew and myself on national TV a few times, making it one of my early career highlights for sure.\n\nMy senior year at UD led to an internship with WHIO, which is why you are reading this now. I am ecstatic to continue to learn and grow in the Dayton market with all the versatile roles I am asked to do with the great people I work with. \n\n\nQ & A\n\nWhere were you born? Hamilton, Ohio\n\nWhere did you grow up?  Hamilton, Ohio\n\nWhat was your favorite TV show then? SportsCenter, I would always pick sports over cartoons growing up if I could. \n\nWhat was the first thing you ever wanted to be? Meteorologist for TV\n\nHow might someone have described you in high school? Smart, hard working, very involved, has a voice for radio and TV.\n\nWhat was your first job? Doing yard work around my neighborhood and for family friends.\n\nWhat was your first job in radio? General Manager of WUDR, but technically WHIO is my first commercial radio job.\n\nWhat do you like about your job?\nThe opportunities I have doing just about everything in radio, from reporting to sitting courtside at UD. Never a dull day.\n\nWhat do you not like about your job? Anchoring during a “slow news day.” It’s a challenge to find anything to air, and then I’ll second guess myself if it’s worth talking about.\n\nWhat might people be surprised to know about you? \nI would rather stay busy and work than to have a lazy day of just sitting around and doing nothing. I think it’s because I hate being bored.\n\nWhat is the hardest thing you ever did?\nContinuing to work and attempt to carry on like usual while my grandfather was dying (his wishes)\n\nWhat would be a perfect day for you?\nHosting a gathering of friends for a sporting event like March Madness or a bowl game. Any combination of entertaining and a sporting event is perfect.\n\nWhat advice would you have for someone wanting to go into the business?\nStay versatile! It takes patience to get where you want to go, but if you always improve on writing and stay willing to do anything, opportunities open up.\n\n\nIf you could only keep one 5-minute tape from your career what would be on it? \nLots of UD basketball highlights, a few of my reports immediately following the verdict in the Trayvon Martin case (my first breaking news experience).\n\n\nFavorites\n\nFavorite book: Battle Cry by Leon Uris\nFavorite radio program:  Bob and Tom\nFavorite dream car:  McLaren F1 and Ferrari FXX\nFavorite food: Chicago Style Pizza\nFavorite hobby: Fixing computers and other pieces of technology\nFavorite Miami Valley place: The great campus of the University of Dayton\nFavorite movie:  Anchorman\nFavorite music:   I’ll listen to just about anything, mostly classic rock and electronic genres.\nFavorite travel destination:    Western United States am one of the newest members of the WHIO team, joining Cox Media Group in May 2013. I have started out my career as an anchor, reporter, and producer for WHIO-AM/FM and will also report on traffic for both radio and WHIO-TV. In my short time with the company I am grateful for learning and working with some of the best in the industry.\n\nI was born in Hamilton, Ohio and attended one of the GCL’s finest schools, Stephen T. Badin High School. It was during my time at Badin I discovered what I wanted to do for my career as I fell in love with the broadcasting industry. I was the public address announcer for many sporting events at Badin, and I had a desire to take the next step into radio and television as a play by play man. If I couldn’t play sports, I wanted to be around them. \n\nI came to Dayton to pursue my dream of working in the media by attending the University of Dayton. I graduated Cum Laude with a degree in Communication with a concentration in Electronic Media and a minor in History. My time at UD directly affected my personal and professional development. I was very active in many parts of campus, mostly the student radio station WUDR and the honors communication fraternity Phi Beta Chi. At WUDR I was a manager for three years, first as the Public Affairs and Sports Director for one year, and a combined role of General Manager and Sports Director for two. I also held the position of Vice President for one term with PBX.\n\nLike previous sports directors before me, doing play by play for WUDR led to some great opportunities, including traveling to the Atlantic 10 Tournament in Atlantic City, New Jersey twice and Brooklyn, New York once. My first year in Atlantic City saw the Flyers make an improbable run to the championship game, but fell short in the final game. Two of my childhood idols, Verne Lundquist and Bill Raftery, calling the game for CBS, featured my crew and myself on national TV a few times, making it one of my early career highlights for sure.\n\nMy senior year at UD led to an internship with WHIO, which is why you are reading this now. I am ecstatic to continue to learn and grow in the Dayton market with all the versatile roles I am asked to do with the great people I work with. \n\n\nQ & A\n\nWhere were you born? Hamilton, Ohio\n\nWhere did you grow up?  Hamilton, Ohio\n\nWhat was your favorite TV show then? SportsCenter, I would always pick sports over cartoons growing up if I could. \n\nWhat was the first thing you ever wanted to be? Meteorologist for TV\n\nHow might someone have described you in high school? Smart, hard working, very involved, has a voice for radio and TV.\n\nWhat was your first job? Doing yard work around my neighborhood and for family friends.\n\nWhat was your first job in radio? General Manager of WUDR, but technically WHIO is my first commercial radio job.\n\nWhat do you like about your job?\nThe opportunities I have doing just about everything in radio, from reporting to sitting courtside at UD. Never a dull day.\n\nWhat do you not like about your job? Anchoring during a “slow news day.” It’s a challenge to find anything to air, and then I’ll second guess myself if it’s worth talking about.\n\nWhat might people be surprised to know about you? \nI would rather stay busy and work than to have a lazy day of just sitting around and doing nothing. I think it’s because I hate being bored.\n\nWhat is the hardest thing you ever did?\nContinuing to work and attempt to carry on like usual while my grandfather was dying (his wishes)\n\nWhat would be a perfect day for you?\nHosting a gathering of friends for a sporting event like March Madness or a bowl game. Any combination of entertaining and a sporting event is perfect.\n\nWhat advice would you have for someone wanting to go into the business?\nStay versatile! It takes patience to get where you want to go, but if you always improve on writing and stay willing to do anything, opportunities open up.\n\n\nIf you could only keep one 5-minute tape from your career what would be on it? \nLots of UD basketball highlights, a few of my reports immediately following the verdict in the Trayvon Martin case (my first breaking news experience).\n\n\nFavorites\n\nFavorite book: Battle Cry by Leon Uris\nFavorite radio program:  Bob and Tom\nFavorite dream car:  McLaren F1 and Ferrari FXX\nFavorite food: Chicago Style Pizza\nFavorite hobby: Fixing computers and other pieces of technology\nFavorite Miami Valley place: The great campus of the University of Dayton\nFavorite movie:  Anchorman\nFavorite music:   I’ll listen to just about anything, mostly classic rock and electronic genres.\nFavorite travel destination:    Western United States That's according to the White House’s National Security Council. As a result, the number of vulnerable systems has fallen by 45 percent.
